Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – The eloquence has always been one of the main assets of US President Barack Obama.
However, it seems today that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After stating in March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react strongly to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of over 1,000 civilians using sarin gas.
Naturally, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why has Obama entangled himself with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
US Secretary of State John Kerry is right to call the use of gas "an act of moral obscenity".
But torturing children, a precursor to the civil war two years ago, is just as much.
And is killing civilians with chemical products any more morally obscene than bombing them, shooting them, or letting them die of starvation?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Large-scale weapons of destruction, particularly nuclear bombs, certainly do more damage and faster than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo with incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas Jews than to massacre them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, holds that a quick punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and revert to "more commonplace means for massacring his people."
A mon avis, cela n’a aucun sens.
La question est sûrement celle du massacre, pas des méthodes utilisées.
Dans tous les cas, l’indignation morale, aussi justifiée soit-elle, n’est pas une raison suffisante pour entrer en guerre.
Mao Zedong a été responsable de la mort de plus de 40 millions de Chinois dans les années 1950 et 1960.
Aucune personne sensée n’a suggéré qu’une intervention militaire en Chine était une bonne idée.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with US support.
Is this a question of legality? The use of chemical weapons constitutes in fact a violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be prosecuted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, by the way, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defensible policy.
One might nevertheless argue that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the leading Western power, must surely draw the line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But where exactly should we draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Thousands?
Thousands?
Millions?
Or does the number not matter?
A genocide, after all, is about intention; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnicity, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance to improve the situation, save lives, and make the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Responding to it implies asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
<s>Comme l’action de la CPI, « l’intervention humanitaire » a plus de chances de produire un résultat dans un pays faible (par exemple la Serbie, le Mali ou le Sierra Leone) que dans le cas d’une grande puissance.
<s>Personne n’envisagerait des tirs de missiles sur la Chine ou la Russie au nom de la défense des droits humains ou pour faire respecter les normes et conventions internationales relatives à la guerre.
<s>La Syrie, comme beaucoup l’ont souligné, n’est pas la Libye ou le Mali.
<s>Elle n’est pas non plus une grande puissance.
<s>Mais la guerre civile qui y fait rage a déjà débordé de ses frontières, impliquant des pays plus importants, dont l’Iran, la Turquie et la Russie.
There can be no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
Actually, some advocates of American intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to wish the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama may have linked in his mind the red line regarding Syria with the one he drew concerning Iran, perhaps just as unwisely, to prevent Iran from developing nuclear arms.
What, then, is to be expected from American strikes on Syrian targets when Obama has already indicated that they are not meant to bring down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But one missile will suffice to make the United States a direct participant in this war, sparking a new wave of violence.
Taking this risk to salvage Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
This may even be Obama's view, which is why he desperately tries to buy time by delegating to the U.S. Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since his presidency began, his relations with Congress have not been easy.
But he now needs this more than ever to cover his back.
